or melee, bow skills as a main weapon, and some magic skills which include a permanent charm animal and insect for a pet and some dex and ac buffs.  The Hibernian equivalent is the scout which also gets the same bow skills but no spells.  Instead they get sword and shield skills which aren't available to me.  Both roughly the same classes but with some minor tweaks to make them noticeably different both play wise and PvP wise.  Now the classes available to you as a player are limited to the realm that you chose to play.  Looking at the number of classes in a realm compared to the number of classes in EQ, EQ wins this contest.  The number of classes in the entire game however is greater then number of classes in EQ, so DAOC wins when you compare game to game.<br><br>Verdict: Tie<br><br>Combat System:<br>I don't need to explain how combat works in EQ so I'll just stick to daoc combat.  Fights in daoc are over quick.  Mobs hit harder and dont have as many hps as comparable EQ mobs.  For example lvl 25 daoc mobs can hit for over 100 dmg against lvl 20-22 players.  However as an archer type I melee with my spear for about 30-40 pts of damage and the tank types are doing 60-110 a round.  <br><br>In EQ high level tanks have disciplines to be used when needed.  In Daoc tanks have combat styles which can be used repeatedley or under special circumstances.  The catch is these combat styles take stamina which drains and replenishes about the same rate it does in EQ however there's no invigor type spell that I know of.  Some of the combat styles can be used at any time, others only when to at the front, side, or rear of an opponent.  Some styles can only be used when you parry an attack or evade an attack.  Some of the more advanced styles have a 1-2-3 combo which must be used in succession with each following style doing more and more damage.  Kinda like a jab, body blow, then uppercut combo in boxing.  When a player succesfully executes a style he gets a message saying how much extra damage was done and you get cool lightsaber like animation effects of your weapons slicing away.  Now IMO a good 50% of the styles are worthless.  Imagine in EQ where you had to sit there and hit a button within one second after you riposted an attack followed by another button to execute a 1-2 combo.  Nice kinda thought but not always practical.  <br><br>Levels make an even bigger difference then they did in EQ.  In daoc you get bonus damage when fighting mobs that are lower level then you and you get damage penalties when fighting mobs higher then you.  For example at lvl 22 I can shoot newbie level mobs for over 100 points of damage and melee them for nearly 100 pts of damage.  Against mobs my level I shoot for around 40-50 and melee for 30-40.  Against mobs 3-4 levels higher then me I shoot for around 20-40 and melee around 20-30.  The same is true for spells, if your higher level then the mob, you do your base damage plus bonus damage.  It would be like a lvl 50 wizard with ice comet nuking a lvl 30 EQ mob for 1800 dmg instead of 1120 or whatever the max damage is.  <br><br>Verdict:  Fights are generally the same except daoc fights are over much quicker win or lose.  The combat styles make tanks stay alert and do something more then hit taunt/bash/slam repeatedley.  Slightly in Daoc's favor here.<br><br>Magic system:<br>Casters and healers get 3 schools of magic to choose from in daoc.  The number of spells available depends on how many skill points the player assigns to each school.  Typically all the spells are the same, the only difference is upgrades to your current ones.  The spirit master for example can have 18 spells for his whole career.  By the time he is lvl 11 he can have all these spells.  These are teh same spells he'll have for his entire career, as he levels up he'll get more spells which are upgrades to the ones he currently has.  So here the magic system is somewhat limited and favors EQ with its rich diversity of spells.  The spells that casters/healers do get are the core staple spells from EQ.  Spells like a DD, ac buff, AE dmg, life tap, etc.  There aren't many utility type spells EQ has.  <br><br>Here's one thing that most people will like though.  Imagine EQ with everyone having perma Clarity 5 and you have the mana regen system in daoc.  At lvl 20 you can go from OOM to FM in less then a minute.  Complete wipeout?  Takes about 5 mins to recover, one player can be resed in about every 30-45 seconds.  Buffs take virtually NO MANA (cheer).  No more 10 minute buff sessions getting ready to get ready.  Instead the game has concentration points.  A buffer can only have so many outstanding buffs out at once, after that they can't buff anyone.  It would be like having a lvl 60 cleric casting 10 Aegis buffs and use one bubble of mana, however after that he couldn't do anymore buffs.  I personally like that system because it cuts down on downtime when your playing while putting a check in to prevent rampant buffing without consequences.  <br><br>Verdict:  Spells variety favors EQ big time, just a ton more spells in EQ then Daoc.  The mana system favors daoc however because downtime is evil.<br><br>Leveling:<br>In daoc you fight nearly constantly because of the super fast mana regen rate and faster hp regen rate.  Also the fights are over about twice as fast in EQ.  However when it comes down to it you level about the same rate in daoc as you do in EQ.  I have about 3.5 days played time and I'm lvl 23 which is comparable to non gimp or twinked EQ leveling.  <br><br>Verdict:  just depends on what you like, a slower paced combat system and recovery rate or one that's faster paced but does require more work because its that many more mobs to kill for the same leveling rate.<br><br>Character development:<br>This is a BIG BIG difference here between these two great games.  Character development in daoc is diablo like because you assign skill points as you level up.  One lvl 50 sorcerer can be very different then another lvl 50 sorcerer unlike in EQ.  Not all characters are the same!  There is a definite distinction in this game which is good!  A healer class in Midgard for example has the unenviable duty of being BOTH Enchanter and Cleric in his group.  Now depending on how he/she spends their points they can be a better enchanter or a better cleric or be average in both but good at neither.  For the tanks there is what you could call weapon specialization in the game.  Axe users get different combat styles then sword users.  Dual wielders get different combat styles then two handed weapon users.  A warrior can specialize in two handed weapon usage and parry skill while another warrior could specialize in one handed swords and shield usage.  Its all in how you decide to make your character and the game puts you in control of how your character is made.<br><br>Verdict: Daoc<br><br>Graphics:  Daoc's graphics are just a touch better then EQs however the EQ engine has been the same for the last 2.5 years so I would HOPE its better.  When SOL comes out I'm sure they will be equal or maybe better in EQs favor.  The 3D engine in EQ is better then daoc's engine IMO.  I played EQ in 1024x800 with good FPS, but in Daoc at 800x600 I get bad FPS with my PIII466.  Spell graphics are comparable, daoc melee graphics are better then EQs because when a tank does a combat move you can graphically see it rather then just get a one line text when a tank uses a discpline.  <br><br>Verdict:  EQ has a better 3D engine IMO.  Graphic quality is about the same but EQ has better FPS.<br><br>Loot:<br>Everyones favorite thing isn't it?  It what most people play the game for, to find exciting new items for your character and it makes the game fun.  Here is another major major difference in the game but I can understand the reason for it.  Magic loot in daoc is almost nonexistent.  There is hardly anything magic to find in the game, the few magic items I have came from quests which anyone of my class can do.  EQ has loads and loads of magic items and the items is what seperates the big boys from the kids in EQ.  This is why daoc has few magic items.  Its because the high end game is going to be PvP that they don't want really poweful magic items out there.  They want the player to win by skill and not by loot.  Sure skill can take you a long ways but you can't tell me that loot doesn't make a major difference in EQ.  Take 50 lvl 60s into NToV armed with planar armor, lamentations, and 30/45 two handed weapons and they'll get hosed.  Now take 50 lvl 60s with full kael armor, primal weapons, dain dorf belts, yelinak gloves, and they'll do good if they have the tactics.  Also who is going to win in a 6 on 6 battle between a group with planar armor and planar weapons against another with SoV armor with a few choice NTOV drops and primal weapons?  That is exactly why there aren't many good items to be had so far in daoc, they want the PvP fights to be player dependent and not item dependent.  <br><br>Verdict:  EQ<br><br>The end game:<br>This is largely a matter of personal preference.  If you like PvM then EQ is your game.  Eq easily wins the PvM game.  There aren't many if any uber mobs in daoc to kill.  I'm sure you would get very very bored in daoc if you played the game for the PvM, it just doesn't have the content that EQ has.  An EQ raid is a raid against an uber mob of some kind, a raid in daoc is a raid against player held lands.  Big difference.  I personally like the PvP aspect of it because after you kill Trakanon 10 times it becomes routine, its always the same and nothing changes.  However a raid against a player held realm keep will always be different and interesting.  EQ grew stale for me because I had experienced almost everything there was in the game.  I think the longevity in daoc will be better for me because I love multiplayer games.  That's why games like Starcraft, Halflife, and Quake are still so popular because of the PvP.  PvE is good and fun but it has a point where it can't offer anything new.  PvP is always different and has more long term viability.  <br><br>Verdict: its your choice on what kind of game that you like to play.<br><br>Final notes:<br>Mythic entertainment recognized the negatives and positives of PvP.  They seemed to have succesfully taken away almost all the negatives of PvP while keeping all the positives.  When you die in daoc in PvP the following is true:<br>-you don't lose money or items<br>-you don't lose experience<br>-you don't lose anything at all!  Its kinda like Team Fortess, you respawn at your starting point with all your equipment.<br><br>When you kill someone in PvP you gain realm points which has been a mystery on what they are used for because nobody has acquired enough of them yet.  So the victor gets a reward and the loser isn't punished in anyway besides being sent back to his start spot in some nearby town.  <br><br>Also the d00D factor is eliminated in PvP in the game.  The game effectively dehumanizes the opposing players.  When you target the other team you don't see any names, you just see their race.  Click on that big guy over there and you get Troll for your target.  Click on the smaller one and you get a kobold for a target.  You can't communicate with the other team at all.  Anything you say they don't see and vice versa.  Tells can't be sent to members of the opposing team.  For all intents and purposes the other players could be GM driven pcs in a big battle.  That means if you get PK'd you don't get any &quot;Joo suck&quot; messages sent to you or any other taunts.  That also keeps crossteaming from happening which is good since we all KNOW that would happen otherwise.  <br><br>Well I'm sure I'm forgetting something but oh well. <p>----------------------- <BR>Zartuul the Tactician <BR>Grave Lord, Zeb <BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#564E39><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=lef