.com/urunei.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Runei</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0> at: 10/22/01 7:18:55 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#564E39><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uaxterixenobelix.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Axterix EnObelix</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grumpy Ol' Gnome</span><br>  Posts: 110<br> <font color=#F4CC10>(10/22/01 7:12:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=557.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: My review of DAOC and comparisons to EQ</span><hr size=1> Well, I found the review somewhat on the mark... and somewhat off.  Some of the things I think Zartuul is missing:<br><br>The big thing is levelling.  So far, (at 15), DAoC blows EQ away.  Up until level 20, you can get tasks which you can do for xp.  These tasks generally encourage you to travel.  You can run errands for non-guards (big travelling time, learn the world, but not really worth the time) or kill-tasks for guards.  The kill-tasks rock.  Instead of in EQ, where you find a camp and stay there until you ding, you get asked to kill something that you can solo... and that thing will differ, sending you to different areas around where you are.  In short, it encourages you to get to know the area.<br><br>Additionally, most everyone can solo an xp mob.  If you don't want a group, you don't need one.  Solo is typically the best way to do the kill tasks (as they are typically blue mobs and groups need to kill higher cons to be worthwhile).  Or you can group, get a bonus for being grouped, fight higher cons which are nice xp, and benefit from things like Group Bonus (a bonus for fighting multiple mobs at once).<br><br>Mobs are also worth more xp if they've been up for a while or if they are part of a camp of mobs (even if pulled solo).  This encourages you to hunt where others don't.<br><br>Because cons change quickly, you're looking for something new to kill in pretty short order.  None of this kill Frogloks for 20 levels.  Move around, explore.<br><br>My verdict: As far as xp'ing goes... DAoC blows EQ away.  DAoC encourages you to explore a bit, EQ encourages you to sit and camp.<br><br>Loot:<br>Another big, big advantage for DAoC.  In EQ, you are your gear.  Your gear makes you different from person X.  You give a melee twink a fungal tunic and he's god.  You want to make money or improve your items?  Camp it or camp something else to make money to buy it.  In DAoC... you kill a named and can get its item 1x.  So again, move on, go find something new.  Quest loots are also something that isn't camped.  No people camping the AC to make money.  Items exist... and they help melees and casters equally.  Get the right gear and your level 5 spell gets more powerful.  Try and do that in EQ.  Gear also cons.  You want blue con armor.  Get stuff thats beyond your level and it degrades fast plus you don't get all the benefits.  In short, most people are pretty equal.  That's right, you don't need to be in a NToVable guild to get good stuff.  You can play with your friends, in a nice small guild, and be happy.<br><br>My Verdict: DAoC, by a long shot.<br><br>Quests:<br>Another big, big thing in DAoC's favor.  See, quest loot only drops if you've been given the quest and are at that step.  And the items you get are very nice.  Better than drops you can get at the same level.  Again, this discourages you away from mass power levelling and encourages you to explore.  At 11, I got myself a staff that adds 10 to my 3 spell skills.  I'm not exactly sure what that means, but it sounds impressive and it blows away anything else that I could get at that level.  The quests are also more interesting in that they give some history, can trigger things (sort of like Coldain Ring war 10), and you can't skip steps.  Go see the world.  Of course, you don't need to have the quest rewards, if you don't want to do them, you don't have to, but they are nice to do.  EQ low level quests... uhm... well, they suck, enough said.<br><br>Additionally, the game helps you keep track of what the next step in the quest is.  You can do this for tasks too.  I do wish the info included a bit more, at least for delivery tasks... the town of the person to deliver in really should be listed.<br><br>My Verdict: DAoC.<br><br>Tradeskills:<br>EQ made their game dependent upon drops.  As such, things sold from merchants or by players have no value.  If not today, then when the next expansion comes out.  After all, as Zartuul said, loot is the primary motivation... in EQ.  Not DAoC.  Here tradeskills would appear to have a real future.  Players basically make the same items the npc vendors sell (more durable though), but can make them for less.  Now, magic items do drop from mobs that are better because of their bonuses, but the con system means people outgrow them or can only use them for a limited set of levels.  As items aren't too pricy, people will let items leave the market by selling them to vendors and because items do get worn down through use, there is always a demand for new, unscuffed stuff.  In short, as far as I can see, tradeskills won't grow useless and need to be bolstered not by making them useful, but by making them a component in a quest.<br><br>My Verdict: DAoC by a longshot.  At least that's the verdict of this disgruntled tinkerer.<br><br>Dieing:<br>Another biggie for DAoC.  The xp loss is sorta hefty.  No 96% resses.  You basically lose 10% of your current level's xp.  But your first death has a significantly reduced penalty.  You don't need a ress.  You want half of the xp back?  Go to where you die and type /pray.  You do lose con, up to a max of 3 (1 point for first death, 2 for second, 3 for every one thereafter) and you need to pay a healer to get your con back, at a rate that goes up each level.  But the fee isn't anything you can't afford.  If you die in a nasty place, you just /release, take the xp loss, and don't go back.  Why?  Because you don't need to.  All your gear pops up with you, nothing gets left behind.  As a last added bonus, you can't lose a level.  So if you've just dinged, it's a great time to go explore.<br><br>My Verdict: Another biggie for DAoC.<br><br>Boats and Port Dependency:<br>DAoC doesn't have them.  Instead, take a horse to where you want to go... if you are near a town that has a horse that goes where you want to go.  Hopefully they'll add more and more horse routes.  <br><br>My Verdict: Another biggie for DAoC.<br><br>Now, there are things EQ does better.  <br><br>Communicatios:<br>For instance, the /who system in DAoC sucks right now.  Can't do /who &quot;dark brethren of midgard&quot;... that's just /who dark.  Can't do /who 1 viking.  That's just /who 1.  Very annoying.  There isn't a hotkey to send a tell.  You can't cycle through different people to reply to.  I miss shout.  I miss OOC.  The lack of these serve to isolate you.  Hopefully they'll add a limited range shout at some time in the future.  The communications window is split in DAoC, a semi-nice idea.  The problem is you can't set the font size... so unless you make a huge window, you've got limited number of lines there.  You can miss a lot of info that way.  Additionally, some fool put the tabs for different communication modes on top of the chat box, where you click to target things.  The smart thing would have been to put them on the bottom, where you won't click on them by accident.<br><br>My Verdict: EQ for now, until DAoC wakes up and fixes up their system.<br><br>Feedback:<br>I can't see how hard my pet hits.  I'd like to be able to.  I don't know how much my damage shield does to mobs.  I'd like to be able to.  I also can't /bug or /feedback to give them my opinions in game.<br><br>My Verdict: EQ, by a pretty big margin.<br><br>Another biggie for me is variety.  In EQ, I'm running around in a world with a ton of races.  In DAoC, there are 4.  Yes, there are 8 more in other realms, but that really doesn't matter.  My guild, my friends are playing in Midgard.  The other 8 are the enemy.  So effectively, that means 4 races.  While you can dye your armor to different colors, so far I haven't seen much variety in looks.  The constant updating of gear also somewhat discourages efforts to customize the look early on.  For character creation, you basically can choose one of 3 sizes and a few faces/hair colors.  But they don't make that much of a difference.  Basically, in EQ, it is a lot easier to recognize someone by their looks.  On the opposite side, you can buy a guild emblem, which should be pretty cool to have on your cloak.  And then there is spells.  I'm level 15.  Since level 8 or so, I have had every ability I'll get.  Henceforth, it's just new versions of the same spells, more powerful.  I hope that they'll add some spell lines that start at 30 or 40 in the specialities.  My pet, even though I've upgraded it 2x now looks the same as it did at level 1.  At least a bit of a tint or size difference would be nice.<br><br>My verdict: EQ.<br><br>Escape potential/short duration travel:<br>In EQ, get SoW, outrun the mobs.  In DAoC, all SoW is a combo of bard speed song and Scale of the Wolf... it drops in combat and you pretty much need to be grouped with the person that casts it to have the benefit.  No asking someone for SoW to make a quick run to something that, in EQ terms, if a few zones away.  If you aren't at a place with horses that go near where you want to go, run at your slow rate.<br><br>My Verdict: EQ, but not by much, as DAoC travel isn't the hassle that EQ travel is.<br><br>Lag:<br>Framerate in DAoC is definately worse.  Especially in the capital city.  They are trying to fix it, but for now, run through the capital, click left to turn left a bit, and you jump your facing 90 degrees.  Very, very annoying.  Other smaller towns also somewhat suffer from this, although not as much.  In the capital though, it's like being on a dragon raid a year ago with full particles on.  It definately makes the capital an unenjoyable place to be.<br><br>My Verdict: EQ, until DAoC fixes this.<br><br>In summary:<br>The game has potential.  At the very least, it's a break from EQ.  From the need to camp, the need to group, the need to do this or that, the frustrations of it all.  It's great to play casually.  And that's the beauty... so far, it's a game.  Not a chore.  If it'll stay that way after I've played for 2.5 years, I don't know.  But for now, it's a welcome break from the monotony that is EQ.  It is nice to be rewarded for doing good things instead of being punished<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Anyway, if you're interested in it and a bit tired of EQ, I advise you to give it a try.<br><br>Axterix Helbound<br>Kobold Spiritmaster of the Dark Brethren of Midgar<br>Morgan LeFay Server <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3F3F25><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ucervantus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cervantus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 166<br> <font color=#F4CC10>(10/23/01 9:45:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=557.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   magic system</span><hr size=1> Everquests magic system works in a similar manner.  We don't get much difference in the types of spells, but those that we have grow in power.  And, they add some flashy names to them increasing the vocabulary of all 