I don't think has been made. Sure, EQ may win in overall amount of different spells, but DAoC casters are more versatile overall. Why? Customizable spell paths. In the high-end EQ game, every caster has a specific role. Wizards nuke, Mages CoH and damage shield, Enchanters.....buff, and Necros are mana batteries. <br><br> Not so in DAoC. Let's look at the Hibernia realm as just an example of versatility. Mentalists, the DAoC enchanter-style class, can dd, stun, mez, heal, charm humanoids, dot heal, and confuse the enemy into attacking themselves. Enchanters are the EQ mage version of the realm, but can slow, cast group sow, stun, dd, and cast a point blank aoe. All more useful than any EQ mage. Eldritch can dd, aoe, dot, debuff str/con, debuff dex/quick, stun, and aoe mez.  I won't even get in to the healer classes because their versatility blows EQ totally away (druids that can res, wtf). <br><br> My verdict: DAoC. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3F3F25><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/usumguror.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sumguror</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#F4CC10>(10/25/01 6:02:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=557.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Is EQ or DAoC More Friendly To The Casual Gamer</span><hr size=1> I usually can only play for about two to three hours at a time.  In EQ, pass level forty, the game has become highly group dependent despite the fact that I have a character that is soloable, a shaman.  Melee types appear to be at the mercy of their ability to find a group.  <br><br>How does DAoC compare to EQ regarding the ability to log on and play when you don't have a large chunk of time to get into a group of people who are near your level?  <br><br>BTW Great reviews so far!  Thanks for the information!   <p>Sumguror Eliyahu <BR>Zebuxoruk Server, Legends of Marr, Barbarian Shaman <BR>Master Baker, Brewer, Blacksmith, Fisher and Potter.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#564E39><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ugondil.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gondil</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#F4CC10>(10/25/01 8:30:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=557.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: My review of DAOC and comparisons to EQ</span><hr size=1> &quot;Verdict: Spells variety favors EQ big time, just a ton more spells in EQ then Daoc. The mana system favors daoc however because downtime is evil.&quot;<br><br>Let's qualify this, because downtime != evil; it actually serves a useful purpose when used in the right amounts.  Excessive downtime is evil, but most people do not understand how much downtime they actually need to enjoy a multi-player game.  These are the same kind of people who come out of a movie saying &quot;too much character development, not enough action&quot;, then see American Ninja on TNT and wonder why it seems so incredibly stupid.  I'm sure Verant is amused whenever they read people talking about how much they hate downtime, how they wish they could leave EQ, they are only playing for their friends, etc.  Verant knows the truth, however:<br><br>Lack of sufficient downtime = lack of player interaction = lack of game longevity <br><br>Games that try to completely eliminate downtime will end up being a 3-6 month &quot;diversion&quot; game between EQ expansions...smart MMORPG game designers will avoid 100% action at all costs:  that's what single-player games are for.<br><br><br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3F3F25><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uaxterixenobelix.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Axterix EnObelix</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grumpy Ol' Gnome</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#F4CC10>(10/25/01 8:41:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=557.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: magic system</span><hr size=1> &gt;&gt;How does DAoC compare to EQ regarding the ability to log on and play when you don't have a large chunk of time to get into a group of people who are near your level? <br><br>Well, at the low levels, most classes can find something worth xp to solo.  Higher level mobs tend to group together more or are found on the frontiers.  Sort of sounds like most people will want groups at that level.  However, there isn't too much high level content yet and I'm quite a distance from it, so I can't say for sure.  I will warn you that 40-50 are very slow, so slow that they put halfway points where you get additional skill points and can't go below once crossed.  By EQ, for the equiv levels you have the 96% ress at that point.  In DAoC, you lose a lot of xp even if you pray, so it is painful.<br><br>In terms of soloability, it does vary a bit by class.  For Midgard, one of the rogue classes is a relatively weak solo'er (their class isn't quite finished yet, missing its spells).  Warriors are also not supposed to solo well due to being defensive in nature, means a bit more downtime.  But I've yet to find a class that can't solo much easier than possible in EQ.  Do keep in mind though that this is still at relatively low levels.<br><br>&gt;&gt;One point I don't think has been made. Sure, EQ may win in overall amount of different spells, but DAoC casters are more versatile overall. Why? Customizable spell paths. In the high-end EQ game, every caster has a specific role. Wizards nuke, Mages CoH and damage shield, Enchanters.....buff, and Necros are mana batteries. <br><br>&gt;&gt;Not so in DAoC. Let's look at the Hibernia realm as just an example of versatility. Mentalists, the DAoC enchanter-style class, can dd, stun, mez, heal, charm humanoids, dot heal, and confuse the enemy into attacking themselves. Enchanters are the EQ mage version of the realm, but can slow, cast group sow, stun, dd, and cast a point blank aoe. All more useful than any EQ mage. Eldritch can dd, aoe, dot, debuff str/con, debuff dex/quick, stun, and aoe mez. I won't even get in to the healer classes because their versatility blows EQ totally away (druids that can res, wtf). <br><br>This isn't entirely true.  To look at Midgard again, yes, our healers can SoW, buff, clarity, heal, and mez.  Our Spiritmasters can play with pet, buff pet, life tap, transfer health, ae mez, and debuff.  However, your skill levels impact resists and ranges of damage/healing.  So a healer that works entirely on healing is a huge asset to a group.  His healing spells are a ton more power effecient than those of a healer that has split up his points.  The same applies to other classes.  To illustrate, my spiritmaster is all summoning (makes me basically an EQ mage).  My pet heal heals about over 1/3rd of my pets health, every time.  The other spiritmaster in my guild is diversified.  He can mez, nuke better, life tap, and transfer health.  But his pet heal is about half as effective as mine and his pet itself would get owned by mine.  Apply that same logic to a healer and you have the difference between having a shaman as healer (can do lots but not that great at healing) and a cleric (super healer, not much else).<br><br>Basically, you have more options, yes.  But you pay a price for it.  When you get a healer, you don't know exactly what you are getting.  You could be getting super heals... or a guy that can mez.  It's a way of taking basic classes and allowing a lot more personalization, a lot more 'classes' than are actually listed.  It is customization.  But when playing my big hp'd warrior, I'd prefer to have one healer that is a near max spec'd healer and another that is more specialized toward the buff and mez aspects.  In short, I want a cleric and an enchanter.<br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page  <b>1</b> <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.showMessageRange?topicID=557.topic&start=21&stop=30>2</a> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.showMessage?topicID=576.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.showMessage?topicID=575.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=557.topic&index=20><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/softsky/addReply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.emailToFriend?topicID=557.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.threadControl?topicID=557.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/softsky/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands (Moderator only)</a><br> <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=557.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=557.topic>Unsubscribe